Oct-26-2010 15:07:15 - Modification to CHIEF COMPLAINT / REASON FOR VISIT, IMPRESSION / REPORT / PLAN by Tracy Fisher

[end section id="20100"]

[start section id="20112"]

Mrs. Ramos was initially diagnosed with a locally advanced cancer of the colon in the area of hepatic flexure with invasion of the duodenum.  A colon duodenal fistula was formed with ulceration in the duodenum and bleeding which was actually the primary symptom of the patient's disease.
At the time when the patient was diagnosed, I was involved in the management decision whether or not we would prefer preoperative neoadjuvant chemotherapy to downsize the tumor.  There was initial concern about the thrombus in the superior mesenteric vein which was suspicious for a tumor thrombus.  Fortunately the intra-operative findings did not show any tumor thrombus here.
The patient did go to surgery first with an en bloc resection of this large tumor and the involved organs including a Whipple resection.  She developed significant postoperative complications for which she has fortunately recovered nicely.  She is actually in pretty good performance status at this point in time.
I reviewed the stage of disease and the overall prognosis of patients with locally advanced, lymph node-positive colon cancer with the patient and her husband.  One complicating issue is that an omental metastases was resected which classifies the patient as a stage IV disease with an M1 tumor.  However, we do not have any evidence of residual tumor at this time so that the patient is, per definition, in the adjuvant indication, our goal of therapy is cure.
I reviewed the rationale and scale to use FOLFOX as adjuvant therapy in her situation.  The patient is aware of the fact that a port will need to be placed to allow the outpatient management of this treatment.  I would like to give the patient a little bit more time to recover and heal.  Our plan is to start chemotherapy on November 1 after Port-A-Cath placement.
I reviewed potential side-effects of this treatment including but not limited to myelosuppression, nausea, vomiting,
diarrhea, and sensory neuropathy.  Mrs. Ramos voiced understanding.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.
ADDENDUM
The tumor was characterized as KRAS wild-type.

