[start section id="20102"]

Poorly-differentiated adenocarcinoma of the right colon with penetration into the duodenum and resected omental metastasis, pT4 N2 (5/53), M1 - Molecular markers: MSS, KRAS wild-type.

[end section id="20102"]

[start section id="20103"]

1.  July 2010 - Malaise, and nausea and vomiting and weakness, Hb of 5.5 g/dL.
2.  August 12, 2010 - CT abdomen/pelvis, EGD. Large colon mass in hepatic flexure  invading into the duodenum causing a bleeding ulceration and fistulous communication between the duodenum and the ascending colon. No overt liver metastases, but non-occlusive thrombus in the superior portion of the superior
mesenteric vein which extends into the main portal vein. Colonoscopy confirms partially obstructing mass at the hepatic flexure.
3.  September 3, 2010 - En bloc extended right hemicolectomy, pancreaticoduodenectomy, with cholecystectomy , end-to-side pancreaticojejunostomy (duct-to-mucosa), end-to-side hepaticojejunostomy, end-to-side duodenojejunostomy, intraabdominal omental pedicle flap (Drs. Cima and Donohue). Pathology:  Poorly grade 4 (of 4) poorly-differentiated  adenocarcinoma forming a 13.5 x 11.5 x 11.0 cm ulcerating mass in  the transverse colon.  Tumor penetrates the visceral peritoneum and  directly invades adjacent duodenum and focally the pancreas. Angiolymphatic invasion is present.  Surgical resection margins are negative.  Multiple (5 of 53) regional  lymph nodes are positive for adenocarcinoma.  The grossly described nodule in the omentum shows metastatic adenocarcinoma.
4.  Postoperative course complicated by anastomotic leak and sepsis as well as acute coronary syndrome of unknown cause with transient reduction of the LVEF to 30-35%.
Mrs. Ramos is a very pleasant 50-year-old patient whose oncologic history is outlined above.  She is now being referred to Medical Oncology to discuss potential treatment options for her locally advanced colon cancer.  Upon presentation today, she stated that she is still recovering from the surgery and the postoperative complications.  Her intra-abdominal drain was removed about two days ago.  She still has some wound dehiscence in the area of the laparotomy.  No fever, no signs of infection.  No pain.  No diarrhea.  Her bowel movements have improved from perioperative diarrhea to now more semi-solid state, and she has about one bowel movement a day.

